  "prompt": "What is the difference between balance of trade and balance of payments?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between balance of trade and balance of payments:\n\nBalance of Trade (BOT):\n1. Focuses only on imports and exports of goods\n2. Measures physical trade of tangible products\n3. Calculates difference between value of goods exported and imported\n4. Narrower in scope\n5. Can be positive (trade surplus) or negative (trade deficit)\n6. Part of the broader balance of payments\n\nBalance of Payments (BOP):\n1. Comprehensive record of all economic transactions between a country and rest of the world\n2. Includes trade in goods, services, investments, financial transfers, and capital movements\n3. Covers three main accounts:\n- Current account (trade in goods and services)\n- Capital account (investments and capital transfers)\n- Financial account (financial assets and liabilities)\n4. Broader and more comprehensive\n5. Always balances mathematically (total credits = total debits)\n6. Provides a complete picture of a country's international economic interactions\n\nIn essence, balance of trade is a subset of the current account within the balance of payments, focusing specifically on goods trade.",
